metadata.name: DisOrder #76
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 84 · 56 · 38 · 26 · 18  every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

All that is, starts with Order.

Order attempts to evade entropy by following its own intrinsic patterns. Then, inevitably, there is change: an anomaly, a nudge that turns into a catalyst for widespread change.The momentum cannot be stopped.

Brief cycles build upon themselves, iterating and breaking into something new with each turn. Now, looking back, the accumulation of small divergences look like a leap, with trails of evolutionary decline casting tall shadows on the patterns that bore them.

The beauty of what this entropy creates, rises beyond chaos. It represents the past, and signals the future, and suddenly looks like a wild take on Order itself – the true DisOrder of life.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

FEATURES :
21 Features implemented including colors, styles, technical parameters...

INTERACTIVITY :
Press ‘h’ in live mode for a list of options.
Press 's' to save an image of the output at the current resolution
Press ‘1’-’9’ to increase resolution
...

metadata.name: a house divided #117
metadata.description:
This piece reuses the same line drawing algorithm from 'this is where i draw the line', meant to emulate a marker drawing on paper.

In terms of composition, we start with a single square, which we divide into two rectangles, either horizontally or vertically. We then repeat this process some number of times for each of the resulting rectangles. Finally, we fill the rectangles by drawing them with lines. These lines
can be either straight or curved.

The collection of inks and papers has also been expanded from 'this is where i draw the line'. Collectors of that piece have been placed on the reserve list as a thank you for their support.

This piece was created using p5.js

metadata.name: Tezumie 1-1 #252
metadata.description:
Tezumie have found themselves in Dimension 1-1, the perfect place for an adventure!

-WARNING-
They may seem to be a cute companion to hang out in your browser, but DO NOT leave them there for extended periods.  

Side effects may include: Missing items in your household, odd behavior in pets, a strange odor, prolonged nightmares, restless leg syndrome, hearing colors, missing teeth, uncontrollable urges, existential crisis, temporary blindness, and a strong appetite for non-edible objects.

Special Thanks to the following creators for permitting traits based on their art/style/projects;

AgataPoison, Craigers , griza, iRyanBell, Jim the Bim, KilledByAPixel, Liam Egan, Littlesilver, lucky26, MarkKnol, ozzie, PersonChen, punevyr, and the creators of MIME x MIME.

-CONTROLS-
(W)-Toggle weather
(F)-Toggle frame 
(C)-Toggle cursor
(P)–Pause
(A)-Shrink
(D)-Grow
(SHIFT + S)-Save image
(SHIFT + G)-Save 4 frames that you can use to make a GIF, see “sketch.js” for further instructions.

Made in p5js.

metadata.name: Ersbla #527
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.

metadata.name: The Managed Miles - part 1 #231
metadata.description:
A bespoke literary chance machine, crafted from a matrix of ranked, hand-crafted options.
The style and tone of the generated output influences the title, to match the poem as closely as possible.

Based on an original poem in four verses. This is part 1 (plus title). 
Parts 2-4 releasing concurrently.

The algorithm that drives the poem is an evolving feature map. Each word has a series of features that, when selected, contribute to the selection of the following words.

In this way, the poem evolves in a way that is deterministic but with very random roots. 

The chance of two transactions generating the same poem from the system is about 1 in 450,000.

Wily Guys [ T : @guyswily / W : wilyguys.com / I : @wilyguys / M : wilyguys.medium.com ] 
Liam Egan [ T : @neuromantic6 / W : github.com/liamegan / I : @liamgegan ]
